      "(0.999, 'There is a GLARINGLY OBVIOUS reason why we ended up here.\\n\\nPopulation of Greater Sydney: 5.25 mil within 12,367 sq km\\n\\nBut look:\\nPopulation of Greater Tokyo: 37 mil within 13,500 sq km\\nPopulation of Delhi: 34.7 mil within 45,887 sq km\\nPopulation of Shanghai: 30.5 mil within 6,340 sq km\\n\\nThese city populations are even dwarfing the population of Australia: 27.4 mil at 7,688,000 sq km\\n\\nSo how do they do it?\\n\\nWhen you go outside today, take a look at your residential neighbourhood. See how big each properties are. See how big the SIDE SPACE of the houses are, the space in between the neighbours.\\n\\nThen come back home and search the IMAGES of “residential street of (above cities)”.\\nNotice something obviously different to your neighbourhood?\\n\\nThe residential area of these cities are dense, with LITTLE to NO SPACE in between neighbours, and often utilise many apartments.\\nI\\'ll take Tokyo to explain, since some of you might have visited there as a tourist and seen it firsthand.\\n\\n\\nTokyo\\'s Urban Planning and Housing Development.\\n\\nHistorical Context\\n\\nTokyo\\'s urban planning has evolved significantly since the 1950s. After World War II, the city experienced rapid growth, leading to a need for extensive housing solutions. The government adopted a flexible approach to zoning, allowing for a mix of residential and commercial developments. This \"lighter touch\" planning has enabled Tokyo to adapt quickly to housing demands.\\n\\nHousing Types\\nIn contemporary Tokyo, two main types of housing dominate:\\n- Single-Family Detached Houses: These are common, especially in suburban areas.\\n- Multiple-Unit Buildings: These include apartments and condominiums, often owned by individuals or corporations and rented to tenants.\\n\\nCharacteristics of Housing\\n- Smaller Dwellings: Many apartments and houses are designed to be compact, catering to the needs of urban residents.\\n- Limited Lifespan: Japanese houses are often built with the expectation of a limited lifespan, typically around 20-30 years, leading to frequent rebuilding rather than renovation.\\n\\nCurrent Trends\\nTokyo\\'s housing market is characterised by a surplus of available units, which helps keep rental prices stable. The city\\'s unique zoning laws allow for a decentralised layout, where residential and commercial spaces coexist, creating vibrant neighbourhoods. This approach contrasts sharply with more rigid zoning practices seen in other major cities worldwide.\\n\\nOverall, Tokyo\\'s planning strategies from the 1950s have shaped a diverse and adaptable urban environment, accommodating a growing population while maintaining affordability.\\n\\n\\n\\nHere is Australia, compared to Japan:\\n\\nOverview of Australia\\'s Urban Planning and Housing Development\\n\\nAustralia\\'s urban planning has historically favoured larger homes and property sizes compared to many other countries, including Japan. This trend is deeply rooted in cultural preferences and the availability of land.\\n\\nSize of Australian Homes\\n- Average Size: The average new house in Australia is approximately 230-259 square meters, making it one of the largest in the world.\\n- Comparison with Japan: In contrast, homes in Japan are significantly smaller, with many apartments averaging around 30 square meters. This reflects Japan\\'s high population density and limited land availability.\\n\\nFactors Influencing Large Property Sizes\\n- Abundant Land: Australia has vast land resources, allowing for sprawling suburbs and larger residential lots.\\n- Cultural Aspirations: The \"Great Australian Dream\" emphasises spacious homes with backyards, which are seen as symbols of success and comfort.\\n- Historical Context: The traditional quarter-acre block has shaped the suburban landscape, promoting larger homes designed for families.\\n\\nCurrent Trends in Urban Planning\\n- Shift Towards Sustainability: There is a growing recognition of the environmental impact of large homes. Urban planning is gradually evolving to prioritise sustainability, with a focus on smaller, more efficient living spaces.\\n- Increasing Urban Density: As population density rises in cities like Sydney and Melbourne, there is a shift towards higher-density housing, such as apartments and townhouses, to accommodate more residents.\\n\\nIn summary, while Australia\\'s urban planning has favoured larger homes historically, current trends indicate a shift towards more sustainable and compact living solutions.\\n\\n\\n\\nConclusion\\n\\nBecause of our house and land size, especially in between the houses, we have simply ran out of room in our cities. People were not planned to live tighter in each street. Instead, we have too much land mass per capita on all the streets across our cities. \\n\\nThe outbacks are probably the only places the government should have allowed such spaces.\\n\\nSo this is the core reason I believe Australia arrived at it\\'s own housing crises.\\nNon future proofed urban planning.\\n\\nTokyo, to this day, has plenty of rental and sales properties with affordable prices, for who ever migrates there. Especially their domestic natives from all over Japan to study and get a job in Tokyo.\\n\\nAnother key element of this country is that there are bullet train and efficient local lines connecting from Tokyo to everywhere else. This train infrastructure makes people to live comfortably.\\nThe bullet train was also their future proof infrastructure from the past. It\\'s plan began from 1930\\'s, then the first line opened in 1964, and extended the lines every decade.\\n\\nSydney\\'s train lines are catching up, but Melbourne and Brisbane have a long way to go.\\nAnd sure, Australia is a big country, but the length from Brisbane to Melbourne is 1376km aerial distance, just like North to South of Japan of 1342km aerial distance. \\n\\nThere\\'s no excuse to link the big Australian 3 cities plus Canberra and Adelaide, with high speed trains with its own dedicated line. Then extend to Perth, Alice Springs, Cairns and Darwin. Then extend to mid size cities and inland towns like Newcastle, Wollongong, Geelong, Bendigo, Tamworth, Dubbo, Mildura, Mt Isa, Katherine, etc. Imagine the domestic tourism flourishing and more people getting to discover their own country. This would bring down the plane prices too.\\n\\nNotice how most of us still need our own car to get around living in Australian cities?\\nBut when you go to Tokyo, NY, London, Singapore, train line infrastructures are great enough to get around. Most locals don’t own a car in these cities.\\nAnd when these people don’t own cars, they tend to walk more, which contributes to be healthier than driving everywhere like we do.\\nThis shows how important trains are in the cities.\\nIn Los Angeles though, the houses are built with large spaces like ours and their train lines are not extensive. Hence everyone needs a car, just like us. But their metro lines are on the plan to be expanded.\\n\\nBuses are good to go around the small streets, but they were never meant to act as train lines. Because it becomes ineffective against mass population.\\xa0\\nYou need trains to move the masses in one go. And the more buses you have, you risk clogging up the road.\\nIn regional country areas though, most people own cars to get around where trains and buses are not available. Fair enough.\\n\\n\\nThe Property Investors?\\n\\nI think John Howard\\'s policy only quickened the crises, but the actual urban planning was already decided long ago, in the 40\\'s or 50\\'s, so it was too late by 90\\'s. Streets with big properties were already set up.\\nBack then, nobody was thinking that we were going to run out of room, and that we get into trouble in the future. People only had an eye for now, to earn easy money now, with property investing with John Howard.\\n\\nMass Immigration?\\n\\nEven if the mass immigration didn\\'t happen, and the housing wasn\\'t a crisis today, eventually, we would have arrived at the current crises by means of natural population growth. Every year, growing number of kids across Australia wants to go to a big city to study, live and become a family.\\n\\nSo the reason for this crisis is that we simply let the city ran out of room, by poor urban planning that was not future proofed. When you search for the most populated cities in the world, none of them look like our neighbourhood. They all planned back in the day, to build a dense housing infrastructure, to be ready for ever increasing population. Whether they are rich or poor country.\\n\\nOur residential area looks the same everywhere in Australia. Perhaps our cities at least should not have been built like this. Perhaps we needed more high rises across wider city area like New York City and Hong Kong. Perhaps more condensed housing could’ve been build like in UK (or parts of Melbourne and Sydney) where properties are narrow and stuck together next to each other. Perhaps rows of apartments could have been built like Singapore, a cookie cutter living but this was the only way for this tiny country to house everybody by any means necessary.\\n\\nPopulation growth is inevitable, and it’s only going to get worse. So make more apartments and high rise offices and shopping centres. Build the bullet/super fast train lines. \\nWe may have ran out of room in our cities, but we have more room in our country. We just need to build outwards, by supporting mid cities to bring big industries with jobs, connect them with high speed trains, then people can spread out to find careers, and enjoy seeing this country flourish again.')\n",
      "(0.9977, \"@Liam-w4h4w I agree Liam. Having a certain level of wealth provides freedom and options. I for example practice gratitude and act of kindness daily. I also live with a knowledge of my families history. I came from a historically significant family who's power and wealth lasted close to 1 thousand years. Following the war some of my family had to exile our homeland, while other part of our family members who live in other countries remain in powerful positions today, kept and increased their wealth.. I learned from a very young age an importance of money/investment and wealth building. I remember when I was around 2 and 1/2  years old, I admired my countess great ant's (grandmothers sister) painting and told her how beautiful she was and how much I loved what she was wearing on the painting. She reminded me that I am very special, kind and wonderful and I have to remember that in life money/investment and wealth building comes first, and  when I grow up I must dress in high quality, look after everything I own, ensure that my shoes is very clean, my hair tidy and my clothes perfectly ironed. She also told me to follow my destiny and to ensure that I grow up to be humble, honest, kind, savvy and protect myself after which she picked me up. I received the same messages from my whole family from a very young age. Taking responsibility for ourselves and building our futures in an honourable, decent manner should be internalised and actioned by all.\")\n",
      "(0.9974, '\\u200b@gasdive I\\'m going to do the least Australian thing, and gloat.\\n\\nTbf, financial wealth is only of many parts deciding the quality of one\\'s life. Many of the wealthiest countries in the world are basically just financial safe havens, wealthy on paper or cost a fortune to live in, (usually all 3) so it balances out. Also we still have one of the highest qualities of life in the world ignoring our inflated estimated wealth from housing with pretty high Purchasing Power.\\n\\nI find the use of the Lucky Country as a reference for modern Australia to be kind of funny. It\\'s generally pretty out of date, and negative.\\nThe Lucky Country\\'s quote is often misinterpreted or taken out of context with the creator later clarified what they meant in a follow up book called \"Death of the Lucky Country\". He clarified as follows:\\n\\n\"When I invented the phrase in 1964 to describe Australia, I said: \\'Australia is a lucky country run by second rate people who share its luck.\\' I didn\\'t mean that it had a lot of material resources … I had in mind the idea of Australia as a [British] derived society whose prosperity in the great age of manufacturing came from the luck of its historical origins … In the lucky style we have never \\'earned\\' our democracy. We simply went along with some British habits.\"\\n\\nOne must consider the original book came out during when Menizes was PM and we had the same guy as PM for about 14 years at time of writing and at time we really were just a conservative backwater former island colony that basically just mimicked Europe and the UK specifically weirdly but also without a coherent unique identity or really much going on. \\n\\nAustralia\\'s cultural identity went through much more dramatic changes after that point as migration happened from places that weren\\'t Britain and the island mentality started to fade.\\n\\nDo Australians have a strong identity now? Not really, it\\'s definitely very \"British-y\" still and we\\'re not particularly outgoing about culture in life leading many to think we\\'re a cultural wasteland. Most of our unique food for instance tends to be described as \"European Ingredients, but with Asian techniques\", or clearly derived from something else. But there is clear differences between the two countries now and distinct Australian styles in cultural works that\\'s not so shunned as forms for cultural cringe or looked down upon by other Australians these days unlike back when this book was written.\\n\\nLater Labor governments were pretty adamant on educating the population, and while I would say we\\'re not outwardly intellectual because Tall Poppies and such we are still one of the highest educated populations in the world statistically speaking granted we need to do better at making use of this economically. Mining and farming despite being major exports are sources of employment for very few people and generally service exports despite being 70% of the country\\'s employment aren\\'t included in export statistics making it very hard to actually count. The CSIRO used to be quite well respected around the world and invented a lot (unfortunately has become pretty much defunded these days though in favour of using international students funding universities).\\n\\nI would also argue it actively ignores much of the reasons we didn\\'t end up like most former colonies that served as purely for looting resources which ended up politically unstable, extremely poor and often way more corrupt than what we are (corruption we have is generally not nearly as bad as what countries are used to) despite also having Westminster derived politics... is because we actually designed a pretty strong and unique system of politics Compulsory voting, mixed electoral systems with preferential voting in the lower house and STV in the upper house which acts as a means for both radicals from minor parties and mainstream politics from majors without granting a bill power without permission of the other, early adoption of women\\'s suffrage and generally strong systems for human rights (without explicitly writing a Bill of Rights) via clear strong separation of powers, and strong political conventions of which the ALP had massively influenced other Labour Parties to follow in their footsteps they were that well organised.\\n\\nSuperannuation as is had basically fixed a problem they knew would happen decades in advance that many countries are now facing which how to finance an ageing population without heavily tax burdening young people and also create investments to run the country and grow it.\\n\\nHow many places can say they have done this? We actually need to be somewhat proud of the institutions we create sometimes.')\n",
      "(0.9973, 'C\\'mon - let\\'s face a fact - rent is recession proof - I\\'ve been paying it all my life - NEVER ONCE SEEN IT GO DOWN and I\\'m in my late 50\\'s, EVEN IN DIRE RECESSION TIMES, but always incrementally increases more than CPI and wage increases!\\nYup, rigged game, hope Jack and his \"walk in front of the proverbial bus\".\\nIt\\'s not complicated but it\\'s multi-dimensional - yup, great analysis there Jack.\\nOne thing we should agree on, the rich get rich, the filthy rich get uber rich, and those at the bottom  keep getting poorer.\\nI can see returns on my Super - I\\'d rather more common sense - get rid of these uber wealthy, uber influential Super Funds that now own a vast majority of the AUS housing market and influence rents.\\nYup, I get a good Super return, BUT pay twice as much in interim through rent (and they also own major shares in everything else, so power, internet/mobile phones, insurance, banking, etc. are all influenced by them).\\nROBBING PETER TO PAY PAUL. But the rich with Capital Reserves get richer, so that\\'s all that matters!\\nONE THING FOR SURE, THE POOR ARE GROWING AND GETTING ANGRIER - THE BILL MUST BE PAID.\\nMigrating north - I did from NSW to QLD and now facing the same challenges - rents going through the roof, cost of living, etc.\\nLove to see Jack in a working class pub pushing his \"poor housing investor / developer\" mantra - better have a bloody strong jaw, and he ain\\'t got one.\\nHousing investment is the #1 issue in this increasingly worthless country - Jack, hope you sow what you reap!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!\\nCheers!!')\n",
      "(0.9972, 'From electricity to rail grids Canadian pension funds are squeezing the profit out of Australian infrastructure. (National Pacific train in South Australia-Wikipedia)\\nFormer Prime Minister Tony Abbott—who was recently appointed to the British Board of Trade to assist the UK in establishing a free trade deal with Australia and has supported a CANZUK free trade zone including “full mutual recognition of standards and credentials, and free movement of people”—spruiked opportunities to invest in Australian infrastructure when he visited Canada as Prime Minister in 2014. He dined with representatives of the Ontario Teachers’ Pension Plan (OTPP) in Ottawa, and according to the 9 June 2014 Australian Financial Review he “said he wants Canada’s renowned pension funds to look more towards Australia and help his government realise its infrastructure plans”.\\n\\nThe problem is while Abbott and Australia courted Canadian pension investment into Australia, Australia has its own massive pool of superannuation funds, almost a quarter of which is being invested overseas. Australia has just $113 billion of the national $3 trillion pool of super invested in local infrastructure, yet we invest $700 billion in infrastructure around the world! This infrastructure funding model is a fraud that only benefits paper-shufflers. In today’s financial climate, pension funds are geared towards high returns and thus their investments more closely approximate a predatory corporate takeover model than investment in infrastructure as a public good. They work in packs, forming consortia and joint ventures to access new markets and pull off takeovers, across borders. They often appear to compete for assets, but in reality they collude.\\n\\nMacquarie Bank, an Australian bank with British origins, has cornered the market with this model, making a fortune out of Public-Private Partnerships (PPPs), where- by governments subsidise schemes to unlock huge private profits. It was Prime Minister Paul Keating’s compulsory super scheme that turned Macquarie Bank into a mammoth money spinner, going all over the world buying and building private infrastructure with public assistance that the public would pay to use—and generating big profits for its investors.\\n\\nCanadian holdings\\nThe following survey of Canadian pension fund invest- ments in Australia is not exhaustive, but it reveals how the Macquarie model has taken off. Bear in mind, these investments are from only the pension sector of just one country! \\n\\nThe Public Sector Pension Investment Board (PSP Investments), which manages pension funds for Canada’s federal public servants, is the single biggest investor in Australian agriculture “with a land and water portfolio valued at more than $3 billion”, according to a 20 May Weekly Times investigation, “Who owns Australia’s farms 2020—the full list”. Funds operated by Macquarie Bank and a US-based company came in in second and third place, according to the piece.\\n\\nSummarising PSP investments, the article reported: “In the past year alone it has been involved in two of the biggest deals in the nation’s history, each worth more than $850 million.” It purchased 12,000 hectares of almond orchards in Sunraysia, Victoria and permanent water rights worth $490 million for irrigation. It purchased the water from the Singapore agribusiness company, Olam, for 25 years with the option to extend it to 50 years. The orchards were previously owned by a consortium of international investors, according to the 3 December 2019 Sydney Morning Herald, which included European private equity manager Schroder Adveq. Almond producers saw up to a 160 per cent increase in profit in 2018-19, over the previous year. PSP has permanent crop investments around the world.\\n\\nWhile a similar Chinese purchase would have generated controversy, Canada’s buying spree doesn’t. Chairman of the Victorian Farmers Federation’s water council Richard Anderson told the SMH: “Really, all you’ve got is a change of ownership, it (the water) has gone from a Singapore-owned company to a Canadian pension fund. It’s a big bulk of water but it’s still being used in agriculture.” In a joint venture with Australian Food & Fibre, in 2018-19 PSP bought a 15 per cent stake in agribusiness Webster Limited, snapping up three NSW farms, and completed its takeover of Webster with a share buy-up in 2020. Webster is one of the largest irrigated farming operations in the southern hemisphere, producing nuts, cotton, cattle and sheep, and running an apiary business.\\n\\nPSP purchased a majority stake in NSW cropping business BFB, and a Victorian vineyard, in 2018. In 2020 in a joint venture with Warakirri Asset Management it purchased the iconic Erregulla Plains farm in WA, adding to its existing stable of farming operations. In another joint venture with Hewitt Cattle Australia, PSP owns 13 cattle stations worth over $120 million, and 15 per cent of organic beef company Arcadian Organic & Natural Meat. It also owns avocado orchards.\\n\\nThe Ontario Teachers’ Pension Plan has around $1 billion worth of investments in Australia. This includes some half a billion dollars’ worth of almond and avocado farms in South Australia and Victoria, according to the Weekly Times. It also owns the country’s second largest avocado farm in WA. Morgans agribusiness analyst Belinda Moore told Farm Online on 9 October 2019 that Canadian pension funds were interested in large-scale investments in corporate agriculture and infrastructure rather than family-farm investments. Money has also gone into pipelines and roads; in 2013 OTPP “took a 70 per cent stake in three telecommunications companies”, AFR re- ported in 2014.\\n\\nIn 2015 Australia was “the target of a record $34 billion in acquisitions” by Canadian investors “who are applauding the nation’s strategy of selling state assets to fund new railways, roads and hospitals”, reported Canada’s Globe and Mail on 16 December 2015. This was an eightfold in- crease according to Bloomberg data. Australia is the destination of choice for Canadian investment after its neighbour, the USA.\\n\\nThe Australian model involves the “Asset Recycling” privatisation initiative (an extension of the disastrous economic strategy of selling the family silver rather than fixing the economy), devised by Liberal Treasurer for the Abbott government Joe Hockey in 2014, and heavily pro- moted in the USA (“Australian fund managers attempt to swindle Trump”, AAS, 20 July 2017; “Union super funds back Liberals’ privatisation scam”, AAS, 2 Aug. 2017). The plan offers states 15 per cent of the value of any asset sold to fund new infrastructure. The Globe and Mail cites Ron Mock, chief executive officer of OTPP, which manages about $155 billion: “We’re there to invest in infrastructure, and they are the model. They’ve figured out how to attract capital from all over the world.”')\n"
     ]
